\chapter{Unveiling the Rewiring Effects of miRNA Oxidative Modification}
\label{chp:unveiling-the-rewiring-effects-of-mirna}


\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:introduction}

The epitranscriptome encompasses the diverse chemical modifications that occur on RNA

molecules after transcription, adding a dynamic regulatory layer to gene expression control \cite{ruden2025uncoveri} .

Over 170 distinct RNA modifications have been identified, with N6-methyladenosine (m6A)

being the most abundant internal modification in eukaryotic mRNA \cite{huo2020methylad} . These modifications

can influence RNA stability, localization, translation efficiency, and molecular interactions

without altering the underlying sequence. While extensive research has characterized

modifications on mRNA and ribosomal RNA, the epitranscriptomic landscape of small

regulatory RNAs, particularly miRNAs, remains comparatively underexplored. Given the

critical role of miRNAs in post-transcriptional regulation, modifications that alter their function

could have profound effects on gene expression networks and disease phenotypes.

Oxidative stress, characterized by an imbalance between reactive oxygen species (ROS)

production and antioxidant defense mechanisms, is a hallmark of numerous pathological

conditions including cancer, cardiovascular disease, and neurodegeneration \cite{pizzino2017oxidativ} . In RNA, 8-

oxoG formation occurs more frequently than in DNA because RNA is typically single-stranded,

lacks protective histones, and is distributed throughout the cytoplasm where ROS are generated

\cite{nie2013dependen} . Studies have demonstrated that RNA oxidation levels are elevated in disease states, with 8-

oxoG accumulation correlating with disease severity and progression in multiple pathological

contexts.

The functional consequences of 8-oxoG modification are particularly significant when oxidation

occurs within the miRNA seed region, the 7-nucleotide sequence (positions 2-8) that primarily

determines target recognition through Watson-Crick base pairing \cite{min2010target} . The 8-oxoG modification

alters the hydrogen bonding properties of guanine, shifting its pairing preference from cytosine

to adenine \cite{eom2023widespre} . This single nucleotide change can fundamentally redirect the miRNA to

recognize different target sequences. Experimental studies have demonstrated that seed-oxidized

miRNAs lose affinity for their canonical targets while gaining the ability to bind previously


unrecognized mRNAs. This mechanism represents a rapid, post-transcriptional means of

reprogramming regulatory networks without requiring changes in miRNA expression levels or

genomic mutations.

In the preceding chapter, we established that edge information, representing regulatory

relationships between miRNAs and their targets, provides unique insights for both clinical

prediction and functional interpretation. However, those analyses operated under the assumption

that network edges are static, determined solely by sequence complementarity between miRNA

seeds and target sites. Oxidative modification challenges this assumption by introducing

dynamic plasticity into the regulatory network. When a miRNA becomes oxidized, it effectively

loses its original target edges and gains new connections to previously unregulated transcripts.

This "rewiring" phenomenon means that the network architecture characterized in Module 2 is

not fixed but can be dynamically reconfigured in response to cellular oxidative status, adding a

new dimension to our understanding of miRNA-mediated regulation.

Despite the significant biological implications of miRNA oxidation, systematic investigation has

been severely constrained by technical barriers. The current gold-standard method for detecting

8-oxoG modifications involves immunoprecipitation with anti-8-oxoG antibodies followed by

sequencing (8-oxoG-IP-seq). This approach requires substantial starting material, specialized

reagents, and considerable technical expertise, making it inaccessible to many laboratories. The

complexity and cost of these protocols have resulted in fewer than ten published studies

systematically examining miRNA oxidation. Furthermore, there is no standardized

computational pipeline for analyzing oxidation data, limiting reproducibility and cross-study

comparisons. The absence of large-scale oxidation profiles across diverse biological contexts

represents a critical gap that hinders both mechanistic understanding and clinical translation of

this regulatory mechanism.


\begin{figure}[htbp]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=0.9\textwidth]{fig-chp4-p043_00.png}
  \caption{Figure 12. . Overview of computational framework detecting miRNA oxidative modifications.}
  \label{fig:overview-of-computational-framework-de}
\end{figure}

This chapter aims to extend the edge-centric analytical paradigm established in Module 2 to the

dynamic dimension of epitranscriptomic modification. Specifically, we pursue three objectives.

First, we develop a computational pipeline enabling detection of oxidative modifications from

standard miRNA-seq data, thereby overcoming the technical barriers that have limited this field.

Second, we apply this pipeline to liver cancer, demonstrating that oxidation-driven network

rewiring has clinical relevance as a prognostic indicator. Third, we construct database resources

to enable community-wide investigation of miRNA oxidation. By treating oxidation as a

mechanism that rewires network edges, we directly extend the MTI-based and topology-based

approaches, demonstrating the methodological continuity across this thesis.


\section{Methods}
\label{sec:methods}


\subsection{Pipeline Design}
\label{sec:pipeline-design}

The foundation of our computational approach is a comprehensive reference library containing

all theoretically possible oxidized miRNA sequences. For each annotated mature miRNA

sequence, we systematically generated variants in which each guanine residue within the seed

region (positions 2-8) was substituted with uracil, mimicking the base-pairing behavior of 8-


oxoG. This approach accounts for both single-position and multi-position oxidation events. The

reference library was constructed for human, mouse, and rat miRNomes, resulting in thousands

of potential oxidized variants. Each variant was annotated with its parent miRNA identity,

oxidation position(s), and predicted changes in target specificity, enabling downstream

functional analysis of detected oxidation events.

Our detection strategy builds upon established isomiR analysis methodologies, which have

proven effective for identifying sequence variants in small RNA sequencing data. We

implemented a hierarchical alignment approach using the miRge framework, first mapping reads

to canonical miRNA sequences and then screening unmapped reads against our oxidized

reference library. Reads aligning to oxidized variants with appropriate mismatch patterns (G-to-

U at predicted oxidation positions) were flagged as potentially oxidized. The alignment

parameters were optimized to balance sensitivity and specificity, allowing for the characteristic

G-to-U substitutions while minimizing false positives from other sequence variants or

sequencing errors.

For each miRNA, we calculated the oxidation ratio as the proportion of reads mapping to

oxidized variants relative to total reads (canonical plus oxidized). This ratio provides a

quantitative measure of oxidation levels that can be compared across samples and conditions.

We implemented multiple filtering criteria to ensure reliable detection: minimum read count

thresholds to ensure adequate coverage, oxidation ratio thresholds to distinguish true signals

from technical noise, and consistency filters requiring detection across replicate samples. The

pipeline outputs comprehensive annotations including oxidation position, oxidation ratio, read

counts for both native and oxidized forms, and predicted target rewiring consequences.


\subsection{Validation Against Gold Standard}
\label{sec:validation-against-gold-standard}

To validate our computational approach, we benchmarked our pipeline against published 8-

oxoG-IP-seq data from a study examining miRNA oxidation in cardiomyocytes under

phenylephrine-induced stress \cite{seok2020position} . This dataset provided ground-truth oxidation profiles

generated through antibody-based enrichment, enabling direct comparison with our


computational predictions. We processed the corresponding input samples (without IP

enrichment) through our pipeline and compared the identified oxidized miRNAs with those

detected in the IP-enriched samples. This comparison assessed both the sensitivity of our

approach (what proportion of truly oxidized miRNAs we could detect) and its specificity

(whether we correctly identified the oxidized positions).

Our computational pipeline successfully identified the key oxidized miRNA (rno-miR-1b)

previously reported to be induced by phenylephrine treatment, with consistent oxidation

positions and expression patterns. Quantitative comparison of oxidation levels between our

computational predictions and the IP-based measurements revealed strong concordance, with

Spearman correlation coefficients exceeding 0.82 for log-transformed oxidation signals. This

high concordance demonstrates that our approach captures the same biological signal as

immunoprecipitation-based methods, while enabling detection from standard sequencing data

without specialized enrichment protocols.


\begin{figure}[htbp]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=0.9\textwidth]{fig-chp4-p045_00.png}
  \caption{Figure 13. . Validation of miRge against the O8G-IP Benchmark}
  \label{fig:validation-of-mirge-against-the-o8g-ip}
\end{figure}


\subsection{Spike-in Control Experiments}
\label{sec:spike-in-control-experiments}

To rigorously characterize the detection limits and potential false-positive rates of our pipeline,

we designed spike-in control experiments using synthetic miRNA oligonucleotides. We


synthesized wild-type miR-122-3p and a variant containing a G-to-U substitution at the seed

region, mimicking the sequence change resulting from oxidation. These oligonucleotides were

mixed at defined ratios ranging from 1:100 to 100:1 (wild-type:oxidized mimic), with pure wild-

type samples serving as negative controls. The mixtures were processed through standard small

RNA library preparation and sequencing, then analyzed with our computational pipeline to

assess detection accuracy across the range of oxidation levels.

Analysis of pure wild-type samples (100:0 ratio) revealed a baseline apparent "oxidation" signal

of approximately 1%, attributable to sequencing errors and library preparation artifacts that

introduce G-to-U substitutions. This baseline rate was consistent across replicates and

sequencing runs, providing a reliable estimate of the technical noise floor. The detection of

oxidation signals scaled linearly with the true mixing ratio above this baseline, confirming that

our pipeline accurately quantifies oxidation levels when they exceed the technical noise

threshold.


\begin{figure}[htbp]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=0.9\textwidth]{fig-chp4-p046_00.png}
  \caption{Figure 14. . Sequencing results of spike-in control.}
  \label{fig:sequencing-results-of-spike-in-control}
\end{figure}

Based on the spike-in results, we established 1% as the minimum oxidation ratio threshold for

confident detection. Signals below this threshold cannot be reliably distinguished from

sequencing artifacts and are therefore not reported. This empirically-derived threshold ensures

that downstream analyses focus on biologically meaningful oxidation events while minimizing

false-positive discoveries. The linear relationship between input oxidation levels and detected

signals above this threshold validates the quantitative accuracy of our approach.


\subsection{Validation in Standard miRNA-seq}
\label{sec:validation-in-standard-mirna-seq}

To further validate our computational approach in biologically relevant contexts, we developed

an experimental platform combining standard miRNA sequencing with 8-oxoG

immunoprecipitation. We generated paired samples from HepG2 hepatocellular carcinoma and

MCF7 breast cancer cell lines under multiple conditions: untreated controls, hydrogen peroxide

treatment to induce oxidative stress, N-acetylcysteine (NAC) treatment as an antioxidant control,

and drug treatment conditions. For each condition, we performed both IP-enriched sequencing

(gold standard) and standard input sequencing, enabling direct comparison of detection

capabilities.

Systematic comparison of oxidized miRNA species detected in IP-enriched versus input samples

revealed substantial overlap. Over 80% of oxidized miRNA species identified through

immunoprecipitation enrichment were also detectable in the corresponding input samples using

our computational pipeline. While absolute read counts differed due to the enrichment effect of

IP, the identity of oxidized miRNAs was highly concordant between methods. This

demonstrates that the biological signal, which specific miRNAs are oxidized, is preserved in

standard sequencing data and can be computationally extracted.


\begin{figure}[htbp]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=0.9\textwidth]{fig-chp4-p048_00.png}
  \caption{Figure 15.  (a) Comparisons of IP and input identified oxi-miRNAs. (b) The sum of mut reads}
  \label{fig:a-comparisons-of-ip-and-input-identif}
\end{figure}

for only IP identified miRNAs.

These validation experiments establish that our computational pipeline enables reliable detection

of oxidative modifications from standard miRNA-seq data without requiring specialized

immunoprecipitation protocols. This capability dramatically expands the scope of possible

analyses by enabling retrospective analysis of existing datasets, large-scale screening across

diverse biological conditions, and routine incorporation of oxidation profiling into standard

sequencing workflows. The reduced technical barriers and costs associated with our approach

open new avenues for systematic investigation of epitranscriptomic regulation.


\section{Case Study: Oxidized miRNA Biomarkers in Liver Cancer}
\label{sec:case-study-oxidized-mirna-biomarkers-in}

We applied our oxidation detection pipeline to publicly available miRNA-seq datasets from

hepatocellular carcinoma studies deposited in the Gene Expression Omnibus (GEO) database.


Four independent datasets were selected based on availability of raw sequencing data, adequate

sample sizes, and inclusion of both tumor and adjacent normal tissues. All datasets were

processed through our standardized pipeline with consistent quality control parameters, enabling

cross-dataset comparison and identification of consensus oxidation patterns.


\subsection{Consensus Oxidized miRNA Identification}
\label{sec:consensus-oxidized-mirna-identification}

To identify robustly oxidized miRNAs in liver cancer, we implemented stringent consensus

criteria requiring detection across multiple independent datasets. Specifically, we required

oxidation ratios exceeding 5% (substantially above our 1% noise threshold), total read counts

exceeding 50 (ensuring adequate coverage for reliable quantification), and consistent detection

in at least three of the four analyzed datasets. These criteria yielded 11 consensus oxidized

miRNAs (co-miRNAs) that represent high-confidence, reproducible oxidation events in

hepatocellular carcinoma.


\begin{figure}[htbp]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=0.9\textwidth]{fig-chp4-p049_00.png}
  \caption{Figure 16.  Identifying oxidized miRNAs in liver cancer normal miRNA-seq data.}
  \label{fig:identifying-oxidized-mirnas-in-liver-ca}
\end{figure}


\subsection{Target Rewiring Analysis: Gained and Lost Target Sets}
\label{sec:target-rewiring-analysis-gained-and-los}

For each consensus oxidized miRNA, we predicted the functional consequences of oxidation by

defining "lost" and "gained" target sets. Lost targets were predicted using standard miRNA

target prediction algorithms applied to the native seed sequence — these represent transcripts

released from inhibition when the miRNA is oxidized. Gained targets were predicted using the


same algorithms applied to the oxidized seed sequence (G-to-U substitution), these represent

transcripts newly brought under regulation by the oxidized form. This target rewiring analysis

provides the functional interpretation necessary for clinical translation.


\subsection{Rewiring Activity Score (RAS) Development}
\label{sec:rewiring-activity-score-ras-developmen}

To quantify the functional impact of oxidation-driven rewiring at the single-sample level, we

developed the Rewiring Activity Score (RAS). This metric is conceptually analogous to the

MTI-based approach from Module 2, but adapted for the rewiring context. For each sample, we

calculated pathway activity scores for the lost and gained target sets using Gene Set Variation

Analysis (GSVA). The RAS is then computed as the difference between lost target activity and

gained target activity: RAS = GSVA(Lost Targets) − GSVA(Gained Targets). A high RAS

indicates strong rewiring effect, with substantial activation of released targets and/or suppression

of newly targeted transcripts.


\subsection{Survival Analysis in TCGA-LIHC Cohort}
\label{sec:survival-analysis-in-tcga-lihc-cohort}

We applied the RAS metric to the TCGA Liver Hepatocellular Carcinoma (LIHC) cohort to

assess clinical relevance. For each of the 11 consensus oxidized miRNAs, we calculated sample-

specific RAS values and stratified patients into high-RAS and low-RAS groups using median

cutoffs. Kaplan-Meier survival analysis was performed to compare overall survival between

groups, with log-rank tests for statistical significance. Analyses were conducted both across all

patients and within specific tumor stages to identify stage-specific prognostic associations.


