\subsection{Mechanistic Insight: OXPHOS Metabolic Switch}
\label{sec:mechanistic-insight-oxphos-metabolic-sw}

To understand why high RAS correlates with poor prognosis, we investigated the biological

pathways differentially regulated between high-RAS and low-RAS patient groups for the Stage

II biomarker miR-10398-3p. GSEA revealed that high-RAS patients exhibited striking

activation of oxidative phosphorylation (OXPHOS) pathways. While GO analysis showed

suppression of classical oncogenic signaling, KEGG pathway analysis identified a compensatory

metabolic shift toward mitochondrial respiration. This OXPHOS-high phenotype has been

associated with tumor aggression, therapy resistance, and stem-like properties in multiple cancer

types. Thus, oxidative rewiring of miR-10398-3p appears to drive a metabolic reprogramming

event that confers aggressive tumor behavior.


