\section{Summary}
\label{sec:summary}

This chapter's primary methodological contribution is the development of a validated, scalable

pipeline for detecting miRNA oxidative modifications from standard sequencing data. By

eliminating the requirement for specialized immunoprecipitation protocols, our approach

dramatically reduces the technical and financial barriers to oxidation profiling. The rigorous

validation through benchmarking against gold-standard IP data, spike-in controls, and paired


IP/input comparisons establishes the reliability of computational detection. The 1% threshold

derived from spike-in experiments provides an empirically-grounded criterion for distinguishing

true oxidation signals from technical artifacts. This methodology enables retrospective analysis

of existing datasets, integration of oxidation profiling into routine sequencing workflows, and

large-scale screening studies that would be impractical with current experimental approaches.

The liver cancer case study demonstrates that oxidation-driven network rewiring has measurable

clinical consequences. The identification of stage-specific prognostic biomarkers based on the

Rewiring Activity Score establishes oxidized miRNAs as a novel biomarker class with potential

clinical utility. Importantly, RAS captures functional information that simple oxidation level

measurements would miss — it quantifies the downstream transcriptomic consequences of

target switching rather than just the chemical modification itself. The mechanistic link to

OXPHOS metabolic reprogramming provides biological plausibility for the observed prognostic

associations and suggests therapeutic strategies. These findings establish proof-of-concept for

clinical translation of epitranscriptomic biomarkers and motivate further investigation across

additional cancer types and disease contexts.

To enable systematic investigation of miRNA oxidation across diverse biological contexts, we

constructed comprehensive oxidized miRNA reference libraries for human, mouse, and rat —

the three species most commonly used in biomedical research. For each species, we processed

all annotated mature miRNA sequences from miRBase, systematically generating variants for

every possible single-position G-to-U substitution within the seed region. Multi-position

oxidation variants were also generated for miRNAs containing multiple seed guanines. The

resulting libraries contain thousands of oxidized variants per species, each annotated with parent

miRNA identity, oxidation position, and species-specific genomic context. These libraries

provide the foundation for our detection pipeline and enable cross-species comparative analyses.

We are actively developing the OximiR database as a comprehensive community resource for

miRNA oxidation research. The planned database will integrate our detection pipeline results

from systematically processed public miRNA-seq datasets, enabling users to query oxidation

profiles across diverse biological conditions, disease states, and experimental treatments. We are


currently collecting and curating miRNA-seq data from GEO and other repositories, with

particular emphasis on datasets from oxidative stress-related conditions including cancer,

cardiovascular disease, and neurodegeneration. Upon completion, this resource will represent

the first comprehensive atlas of miRNA oxidation modifications, catalyzing research into

epitranscriptomic regulation and its clinical implications.

